# Dreaming Mode Cron Strategy

## Purpose

This document defines scheduling guidance for ACS/OpenClaw Dreaming Mode.

Cron-triggered dreaming should improve continuity without creating cron storms, duplicated summaries, conflicting memories, or uncontrolled canonical writes.

## Scheduling Principles

- Do not wake all agents at the same minute.
- Stagger schedules by agent and layer.
- Keep local dreams short and scoped.
- Run nucleus dreams only for active nuclei with relevant changes.
- Run ACS Coordinator Dreaming after local and nucleus dreams are available.
- Run Core Memory Review weekly or manually.
- Cron jobs must write to structured output paths.
- Cron jobs must not directly mutate canonical memory unless a future approved Core workflow allows it.
- Cron jobs must not execute production actions, trading, treasury, runtime shell, MCP tools, or code changes.

## Recommended Frequency

| Routine | Frequency | Notes |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Agent Local Dreaming | Every 6 or 12 hours | Stagger by agent |
| Nucleus Dreaming | Daily | Only for active nuclei with relevant changes |
| ACS Coordinator Dreaming | Daily or every 2 days | Run after local/nucleus outputs |
| Core Memory Review | Weekly or manual | Review candidates before canonical promotion |

## Example Staggered Schedule

These commands are examples/pseudocode. Confirm exact OpenClaw CLI syntax before use.

```cron
# Agent Local Dreaming
15 1,13 * * * openclaw agents run morpheus /dreaming --mode=local
25 1,13 * * * openclaw agents run trinity /dreaming --mode=local
35 1,13 * * * openclaw agents run agentsmith /dreaming --mode=local
45 1,13 * * * openclaw agents run redhat /dreaming --mode=local

# Nucleus Dreaming
05 2 * * * openclaw agents run coordinator /dreaming --mode=nucleus --nucleus=governance
15 2 * * * openclaw agents run coordinator /dreaming --mode=nucleus --nucleus=trading
25 2 * * * openclaw agents run coordinator /dreaming --mode=nucleus --nucleus=acs

# ACS Coordinator
10 3 * * * openclaw agents run coordinator /dreaming --mode=global

# Core Memory Review
0 9 * * 1 openclaw agents run core-archivist /dreaming --mode=memory-review
```

## Output Path Policy

Recommended output paths:

```text
~/.openclaw/main_workspace/dreaming/outputs/agents/<agent-name>/
~/.openclaw/main_workspace/dreaming/outputs/nuclei/<nucleus-name>/
~/.openclaw/main_workspace/dreaming/outputs/coordinator/
~/.openclaw/main_workspace/dreaming/outputs/memory-candidates/
~/.openclaw/main_workspace/dreaming/outputs/registry-sync/
```

Suggested filename patterns:

```text
YYYY-MM-DD-local-dream.md
YYYY-MM-DD-nucleus-dream.md
YYYY-MM-DD-global-digest.md
YYYY-MM-DD-memory-candidates.md
YYYY-Www-core-memory-review.md
```

## Load Management

To avoid noisy or excessive dreaming:

- skip local dreaming if no relevant context changed;
- cap output length where practical;
- keep raw logs out of memory proposals;
- store only structured summaries;
- deduplicate repeated conclusions;
- mark uncertainty and unresolved conflicts.

## Cron Safety Rules

Cron-triggered dreaming must not:

- call MCP tools;
- execute runtime shell;
- access network tools unless explicitly authorized;
- mutate source/config/runtime/auth/bindings;
- install packages;
- restart services;
- deploy;
- execute trading or treasury actions;
- write to canonical Core memory directly;
- persist secrets or private data.

## Change Control

Do not modify existing cron jobs until:

1. this Core policy is accepted;
2. agent prompts are aligned to the policy;
3. output paths are confirmed;
4. schedule staggering is reviewed;
5. rollback/disable procedure is documented.
